Submit a letter of interest and non-instructional application and copy of nursing license to Personnel Dept. as soon as possible.

Here are some answers to commonly asked questions:
üê∫A Chromebook will be provided to every Harbor Creek School District registered student.
üê∫There is no need to reserve/preregister for a Chromebook.
üê∫We understand some households may have blended families with multiple last names. Because of the volume of students and logistical planning, we ask that you come on the assigned day of the student's last name. No Chromebook will be available to the last name that is not within the range of that designated day.
üê∫HC Cyber Academy students follow the same Chromebook distribution schedule.
üê∫Students are expected to use a Chromebook at school and at home.
üê∫There will be make-up dates announced if you are unable to attend your scheduled day.

shared_text:
Harbor Creek Marching Huskies Band
May 1 at 3:43 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to Harbor Creek Huskies clarinet player Caden Vanderburg for his selection to PMEA All-State Concert Band!!! Caden is a Junior member of the band and qualified for State Band last year as well.

Caden joins Mackenzie Vollant and Simon Weber (both All-State Chorus) as Harbor Creek students and Marching Huskies that qualified for PMEA All-State ensembles. Due to school cancellation, PMEA was forced to cancel the All-State Festival that was to have taken place last weekend in the Poconos.

We are so proud of our Marching Huskies and their accomplishments even in the face of this spring's adversity. Congratulations to Caden, Mackenzie, and Simon!!!!!

Since the school closing announcement on March 13th, members of the community have asked countless times, ‚ÄúHow can we help?‚Äù Now‚Äôs your chance!

Harbor Creek School District is looking for people in the community to ‚ÄúAdopt-A-High School Senior‚Äù for four weeks, from May 11 to June 4. The District will provide you the name and contact information for one of our seniors. You would be asked to support that senior by sending small notes, congratulatory cards, or a small gift during those four weeks, culminating on June 4th.

If you are interested in ‚Äúadopting-a-senior‚Äù please email Maria McGill at mmcgill@harborcreeksd.com and provide your name and email. The District will provide you the name and contact information of your ‚Äúadopted‚Äù senior before May 11th.

post_text:
This morning, the Secretary of Education issued an order under Act 13 of 2020 to close all public schools through the end of the 2019-2020 academic year.

While I am sure this announcement may provoke additional questions, it is my hope that this order provides our District clarity as we plan the remainder of the school year. Online schooling will continue through the end of the school year.

We will continue to plan and communicate to you frequently as any new information becomes available.

Kelly Hess
HCSD
Superintendent

post_text:
Parents:

We are aware that you may be experiencing issues when logging into Schoology. Please know that this is not your fault or an issue with the Harbor Creek School District. It is on Schoology's end.

Please see the message from Schoology below:

Update: We are actively monitoring an unprecedented, rapid increase in concurrent users on Schoology. We have taken a number of steps to improve stability and have proactively added significant additional capacity. During this time, a very small percentage of users may occasionally experience intermittent page loading errors. Refreshing the page should resolve the issue.

Our top priority is to provide site stability and availability and expect to have complete resolution as soon as possible.

Please be patient and flexible as they continue to work on this issue.

post_text:
Good afternoon. You might have seen a news headline earlier today that reported Erie City Public Schools were closed indefinitely. This headline was quite misleading. Upon reading the entire article, it stated that daily distribution of meals would continue but the scheduled distribution of technology devices and paper packets was suspended. Further, it went on to report that the district had not made any decisions regarding the remainder of the year.

While social media can be positive and effective in communicating with the community, please know our District would communicate with you directly regarding the most significant decisions as they are made.

This weekend, I will touch base and publish an update to let you know all that has happened in our District this past week.

Respectfully,
Kelly S. Hess
Superintendent

post_text:
The Autism Society of Northwestern Pennsylvania is an organization that promotes the active and informed involvement of family members and individuals with autism in the planning of individualized, appropriate services and supports. April is Autism Awareness month and each year Harbor Creek has a fundraiser and donates the proceeds to the Autism Society of NWPA. By purchasing Autism Awareness apparel you are helping us to raise money while showing others that Harbor Creek supports individuals with Autism.
Thanks in advance for your support!

Our goal is to assemble as many Easter baskets as we can for underprivileged children and teens in our community. We are partnering up with the Ella Cochran food pantry to distribute them. Please consider donating items for the baskets or making a monetary donation. Every donation will help! We hope to make a big difference in our HC community. Thank you in advance for your generosity! #HCproud #HCBeTheOne Collection dates are March 23-April 3.

Molly Neilsen broke the HC 200 free style record 159.75, 100 freestyle record 54.11, and 50 freestyle record 25.37. Morgan Ingalls broke the HC 100 backstroke record 102.46. Molly, Anna Daley, Madeline Curtis and Erin Ingalls broke the HC 200 freestyle record 142.41. Parents with students in grades 8-11 this year are welcome to attend. Please plan on attending to understand the many benefits of these opportunities. Many of these options allow students to receive college credits while still in high school. The evening will be informational as well as allowing parents (and students) to ask questions to administrators, teachers and counselors.

If you need any additional information, please feel free to call the High School Counseling Office (814)897-2100 ext. 1211

text:
The ANNA Shelter
December 18, 2019 at 8:53 PM ¬∑

Yesterday we visited Klein Elementary School's 2nd grade class with Sandy. The class raised donations for the shelter through the month of November - 4 students were selected to visit us...and we were so touched by their generosity that we decided we wanted to visit all of them!

post_text: Second grade at Klein raised almost $400 to donate to the Anna Shelter this Christmas. They chose to donate instead of doing a gift exchange. Much thanks to Ruth (who founded the Anna Shelter) and Officer Eric Duckett for bringing Sandy to visit today.

Save the Date: 11/14/19 "If Only You Knew" is a FREE event and is open to the public.
There will be speakers educating parents, students, and legislators as to the issues of mental health and addiction in the hopes to bring about awareness and change.
*** UPDATE: Jayson Williams, former 76‚Äôer/ Nets NBA player, and Sean Nassif, former MMA fighter, will be sharing their message of hope at this event. Through their Rebound for Life recovery model, these men are selflessly coming to bring about change. Recovery works! Those suffering with mental health issues and/or addiction will know you are not alone!

Ultimately, the night is meant to break the silence and stigma of both mental health and addiction.
